# StealthQL Cursor Rules

This repo uses StealthQL, a repo-native backend capsule runtime.

Do not assume GraphQL, Apollo, Prisma, Supabase, Firebase, or a hosted database dashboard. Do not search for GraphQL endpoints or resolvers unless the user explicitly asks for GraphQL.

Use this model:

- Backend source files are `stealth.schema.*`, `stealth.auth.*`, `stealth.functions.*`, `stealth.storage.*`, `stealth.sync.*`, `stealth.shares.*`, `stealth.compliance.*`, `stealth.seeds.*`, and `stealth.policy.test.*`.
- Generated capsule file is `.stealthql/capsule.json`; do not edit it or commit `.stealthql/`.
- Private runtime state lives outside the repo by default. If `STEALTHQL_DATA_DIR` is set, keep it outside the project and deploy output.
- Local runtime URL is printed by `npx stealthql dev`; do not assume a fixed port.
- Next.js browser integration uses `/api/stealthql/*` as a same-origin proxy.
- Browser app code should import from `stealthql/next/client`; server routes and Server Components should import from `stealthql/next/server`.
- StealthQL ships TypeScript declarations. Do not add broad `declare module "*.js"` workarounds; they break Next route type checking.
- For non-Next apps, use `stealthql/client` for browser/app code, `stealthql/vite`, `stealthql/sveltekit`, or `stealthql/astro` for framework proxy adapters, `stealthql/server` for generic server code, and `stealthql/schema` for typed capsule authoring.
- `npx stealthql capsule build` emits `.stealthql/client.d.ts`; include it in TypeScript projects for schema-specific table and mutation types.
- If upgrading StealthQL or a consumer app across versions, read `CHANGELOG.md` before making code or schema changes.
- Keep `stealth.schema.request.json` in the app root only while it is the active schema request. Packaged samples live under `examples/`; applied backend truth is `stealth.schema.*`.
- Query rows include `$key` plus `$handles.read`, `$handles.update`, and `$handles.delete`. Use `$key` for UI identity and `handle: row.$handles.update/delete` for user mutations; do not build user flows around raw ids or put handles in URLs.
- Share portal URL tokens should be exchanged once for share-scoped HttpOnly cookies and removed from the URL. Production proposal/CSV requests should rely on the cookie, not raw actor fields.
- Use `createStealthServiceClient` plus `serviceAccounts` for Stripe webhooks, signup provisioning, cron, and background jobs. Never use demo actors like `alice` as service accounts.
- Use narrow service scopes such as `provisioning:write`, `projects:read`, `projects:write`, `projects:delete`, `billing:read`, `billing:write`, `billing:delete`, `share:issue`, and `share:manage`.
- Session actors carry `activeOrgId`; use `actor.activeOrgId` for tenant boundaries. Do not use every `actor.orgIds` value unless building an explicit cross-business view.
- Magic-link auth can return `requiresOrgSelection: true`; show an org picker and verify with `stealth.auth.verifyMagicLink(token, { orgId })`.
- If a user cannot receive email, use one-time recovery codes with `stealth.auth.createRecoveryCode(...)` and `stealth.auth.verifyRecoveryCode(...)`; do not add passwords or raw actor impersonation.
- DigitalOcean deployment docs live at `docs/DIGITALOCEAN_DEPLOYMENT.md`; the hardened Ubuntu bootstrap script is `scripts/digitalocean-ubuntu-setup.sh`.
- Vercel frontend + DigitalOcean runtime docs live at `docs/VERCEL_DIGITALOCEAN_SPLIT.md`; plan the split with `npx stealthql deploy split --frontend-url https://app.example.com --backend-url https://api.example.com --write`.

StealthQL offers:

- Local PGlite-backed capsule runtime, generated TypeScript client types, local auth emulator, magic links, recovery codes, invites, and org selection.
- Policy-bound row handles for browser/mobile mutations, service clients for trusted jobs, backend functions with side-effect ports, policy-bound storage buckets, sync shapes, table/row shares, proposal mode, CSV round trips, portals, compliance evidence packs, export/eject bundles, policy tests, security tests, and DigitalOcean split/single deploy plans.

Schema changes:

- Do not add `organizations`, `users`, or `memberships` to app schema requests; StealthQL generates secure auth/org tables.
- When one table belongs to another, use a required indexed text field such as `Customer Id`, `Project Id`, `Order Id`, `Job Id`, or `Invoice Id`; do not invent unsupported foreign-key types.

Raw ID mutation:

- Browser/mobile update and delete flows must use row handles.
- Only trusted server code should use `stealth.unsafe.mutateById(...)`, and only when the user explicitly needs an escape hatch.
- Never put row handles in URLs or logs.

Shares and portals:

- Use `stealth.shares.*` for table/row shares; shares are delegated grants, not org memberships.
- Use share APIs for `readShare`, proposals, accept/reject, CSV export, and CSV import.
- CSV imports become proposals, not direct mutations.
- Hosted share portals use share tokens or share-scoped HttpOnly cookies; production portal forms must not post raw local actors.

Backend functions and ports:

- Define backend behavior in `stealth.functions.*`.
- Functions receive `ctx` with actor, query, mutate, ports, capsule, and mode.
- Use `ctx.ports` for email, webhooks, payments, and side effects; do not hand-roll `NODE_ENV` branches for side effects.
- Function execution is governed by `stealth.auth.*` `functionPolicies`.

Storage:

- Define buckets in `stealth.storage.*`; do not build custom upload tables unless the user asks.
- Use `stealth.storage.*` for list, upload, get, and delete.
- Bucket policies use `actor.activeOrgId` and `actor.activeMembership` just like table policies.

Sync/data shapes:

- Use `stealth.shape(name)` for reusable policy-bound app data.
- Define shapes in `stealth.sync.*`; shapes can restrict fields and read scope.
- Prefer shapes, generated clients, and functions over ad hoc SQL for app-facing data.

Compliance:

- Define evidence mappings in `stealth.compliance.*` for tables, storage buckets, shares, functions, and data classes.
- Use `npx stealthql audit-report --framework soc2-cc7 --out evidence/soc2-cc7` to generate JSON/Markdown evidence bundles from the capsule and ledger.
- Treat audit reports as compliance-readiness evidence packs, not automatic certification or legal advice.

Security tests are part of the product. Do not skip them. They should catch tenant leaks, share leaks, hidden-field exposure, raw-ID mutation bugs, row-handle misuse, CSV proposal safety, and production deployment misconfigurations.

Use this client for local demos only. Do not use `actor: "alice"` in production code.

```js
import { createStealthNextClient } from "stealthql/next/client";

const stealth = createStealthNextClient({ actor: "alice" });

await stealth.query("projects");
await stealth.sql("select id, name from projects;");
await stealth.mutate("projects", "insert", {
  id: "proj_new",
  orgId: "org_acme",
  ownerId: "user_alice",
  name: "New Project",
  visibility: "private"
});
await stealth.auth.signInAs("alice");
```

For Server Components, server actions, or API routes:

```js
import { headers } from "next/headers";
import { createStealthServerClient } from "stealthql/next/server";

const stealth = createStealthServerClient({
  headers: await headers()
});
await stealth.query("projects");
```

For schema/auth changes, write `stealth.schema.request.json`, then run:

```powershell
npx stealthql schema preview --file stealth.schema.request.json
npx stealthql schema apply --file stealth.schema.request.json --test
```

After backend changes, run:

```powershell
npx stealthql test policies
npx stealthql test security
```

For DigitalOcean Droplets:

- Run `npx stealthql deploy self` before deploying.
- For an interactive deploy menu, run `npx stealthql deploy`.
- For Vercel frontend + DigitalOcean runtime, run `npx stealthql deploy split --frontend-url https://app.example.com --backend-url https://api.example.com --write`.
- Keep one repo with two targets: Vercel deploys the Next app and `/api/stealthql/*` proxy; DigitalOcean deploys the same repo as the capsule runtime.
- In Vercel set server-only `STEALTHQL_URL=https://api.example.com` and public `NEXT_PUBLIC_STEALTHQL_API=/api/stealthql`.
- For one Droplet running both the website and runtime, run `npx stealthql deploy single --domain https://app.example.com --repo <repo> --write` or set `DEPLOY_WEB=true`; nginx should proxy to Next.js on `127.0.0.1:3000`, and Next should call StealthQL privately on `127.0.0.1:8787`.
- Use `APP_REPO`, `APP_NAME`, `DOMAIN`, `LETSENCRYPT_EMAIL`, and optionally `RUN_SECURITY_TESTS=true` with `scripts/digitalocean-ubuntu-setup.sh`.
- Preferred flow is `/root/stealthql-do-setup.sh plan`, then deploy, then `/root/stealthql-do-setup.sh doctor`.
- The agent should fill variables and run the audited script; do not improvise root-level SSH, firewall, nginx, systemd, certbot, backup, or chmod/chown commands.
- Keep the runtime behind nginx: public traffic goes to 80/443, nginx proxies to `127.0.0.1:<STEALTHQL_PORT>`.
- Runtime state belongs in `/var/lib/stealthql/<app>` or another `STEALTHQL_DATA_DIR` outside the repo.
- Secrets belong in `/etc/stealthql/<app>.env`; never put service tokens in `NEXT_PUBLIC_*`.
- Do not expose port 8787 publicly.
- Do not hardcode local actors in deployed routes; forward sessions, bearer tokens, API keys, or share tokens.
- Configure explicit `authConfig.production.allowedOrigins` before production deployment; an empty production origin list should block readiness.

Production red flags:

- `actor: "alice"`, `actor: "bob"`, or another local actor in deployed code.
- `STEALTHQL_URL` exposed through `NEXT_PUBLIC_*`.
- Browser code calling the runtime URL directly instead of `/api/stealthql/*`.
- The StealthQL runtime port exposed publicly.
- Empty `authConfig.production.allowedOrigins` or redirect/callback origins before deployment.
- Share proposal or CSV requests posting actor fields in production portals.
- Raw-id update/delete from browser or mobile code.
- `STEALTHQL_DATA_DIR` inside the repo or deploy artifact.
